UK economy shrinks
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
The <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-15-03-2025-h2-2-uk-economy-contracted?source=website" target="_blank">UK economy contracted by 0.1%</a> in January 2025, contrary to economists’ expectations of 0.1% growth. This poses a challenge for Chancellor Rachel Reeves ahead of her spring statement. The downturn was driven by a 1.1% decline in manufacturing output and construction slowdowns due to poor weather, with only a 0.1% rise in services.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Reeves attributed the contraction to global economic uncertainty, emphasizing that planned defense spending increases would boost the economy. Financial markets anticipate the Bank of England will hold interest rates at 4.5% next week, with a possible cut in May. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The British pound edged lower but remained stronger over the week. Analysts suggest economic growth could rebound in Q1 2025, provided government policies ensure stability rather than cause uncertainty. Lobby groups cite the upcoming rise in employer national insurance payments and minimum wage in April as reasons for a fall in boardroom confidence levels.</p>
        </mj-text>
