          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Saudi Arabia’s Neom project, a futuristic megacity, is facing major financial troubles. Around $50 billion has been spent on the planned $1.5 trillion, 105-mile-long, carbon-neutral smart city, which is now delayed and may take another 55 years to complete, costing an estimated $8.8 trillion. Challenges include labor shortages, lack of infrastructure, and rising costs.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">However, consulting firm McKinsey reportedly benefits, earning $130 million annually. <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-15-03-2025-wn1-3-gulf-media-argues?source=website" target="_blank">Gulf media argues</a> that Western criticism of Neom overlooks the region’s oil-money-fueled rapid economic growth, that mistakes and delays in large projects are natural, and that reports of failure are exaggerated.</p>
