          <h2 style="             
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">What is the Kuznets Curve?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/kuznets-curve-diagram-economic-development-inequality.jpg" alt="Diagram of the Kuznets Curve" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Diagram of the Kuznets Curve.</i></p>
        </mj-text> 
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-15-03-2025-f1-16-kuznets-curve?source=website" target="_blank">Kuznets Curve</a> is an economic theory that shows how income inequality changes as a country develops.</p>  

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Early stage (rising inequality):</strong> At the start of development, wealth is concentrated in cities and among a few wealthy individuals, increasing the gap between the rich and poor.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Industrialization effect:</strong> As economies shift from farming to industry, urban wages rise, but rural areas still struggle, leading to higher inequality.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Turning point (peak inequality):</strong> After reaching a certain level of development, countries invest.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Later Stage (falling inequality):</strong> As the economy grows, workers get better wages, and governments provide welfare programs, reducing inequality.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span><strong>Environmental Kuznets Curve (EKC):</strong> A similar idea applies to pollution. Industrialization first increases pollution, but later, richer societies invest in cleaner technology, reducing environmental damage.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>Example:</strong> Economic liberalization in the 1990s led to rapid growth but increasing inequality, as wealth concentrated in cities while rural areas lagged. In Mexico, economic reforms in the 1990s increased growth but failed to significantly reduce inequality, partly due to corruption and weak wage policies.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
